game_explanation:
This is a 6-round public goods game with costly, anonymous punishment. Each round each player privately has 20 coins and chooses how many to contribute to a shared pot; contributions are multiplied by 1.9 and split equally. The private marginal return on one coin (1.9/3 ≈ 0.633) is less than 1, so purely self-interested play would be to contribute 0 each round. However, group payoff is maximized if everyone contributes everything (20). The punishment option allows players to punish low contributors at a cost (4 coins per punishment unit to the punisher, 12 coins deducted from the target per unit). Because punishment is costly and anonymous, we expect few but meaningful punishment actions early on to establish cooperation norms, then higher contributions through the middle rounds. Toward the end (rounds 5–6) some end‑game temptation may cause defections; whether others punish in the final rounds depends on how strongly they value norm enforcement despite the cost.

Given the three personas:
- SLOTH (older, more inclined to free-ride in the absence of enforcement) will start relatively low but respond to punishment by increasing contributions;
- GORILLA (pragmatic, moderate) will use moderate contributions and use punishment to enforce norms occasionally;
- DUCK (younger, more pro-social) will tend to contribute more early and use punishment to discipline clear free-riding.

Punishment will be sparse and targeted at below-average contributors; chat is infrequent and used to coordinate or complain. Below is a predicted round-by-round transcript consistent with those priors.

